INSERT INTO public.oghma VALUES ('satakal', 'Satakal, the Worldskin, is the Yokudan god of creation, destruction, and the endless cycles of existence. Known as the First Serpent, Satakal embodies the fusion of Anu and Padomay, symbolizing both chaos and order. In Yokudan mythology, Satakal devours entire worlds, shedding its skin to birth new ones, a process that has occurred countless times. This eternal cycle inspired the birth of spirits like Ruptga, the first to learn how to survive these transitions, who later formed the Yokudan pantheon. Satakal''s cycles echo the Redguard understanding of mortality and the longing for the Far Shores, the ultimate spiritual haven they believe lies beyond the reach of mortal life.

Worship of Satakal is prevalent among Redguard nomads of the Alik''r Desert, where the deity is revered as both destroyer and creator. Rituals dedicated to Satakal often involve symbolic "shedding of skin," and its devotees weave the serpent into their maps and lives as a reminder of the god''s dominion over all. Some groups, such as the Pyre Watch and Hunding’s sword-singers, interpret Satakal''s influence as a call to cast aside fixed destinies in pursuit of transcendence. Satakal’s worship is deeply rooted in Redguard culture, influencing not only their spiritual practices but also their myths, oaths, and settlements, such as the city of Satakalaam. Despite Satakal''s profound role in their heritage, his followers have often clashed with more modern Imperial beliefs, reflecting the tension between the god''s timeless cycles and the structured order of the Eight Divines.', '''alik'':121B ''all'':164B ''also'':210B ''among'':116B ''and'':12B,29B,34B,91B,132B,144B,153B,172B,214B,249B ''anu'':28B ''as'':19B,129B,155B,168B,182B,217B ''asid'':187B ''beliefs'':239B ''believ'':103B ''betw'':243B ''beyond'':105B ''birth'':47B,62B ''both'':32B,130B ''but'':209B ''call'':184B ''cast'':186B ''cha'':33B ''city'':219B ''clash'':234B ''countless'':55B ''creation'':10B ''creator'':133B ''cultur'':202B ''cycle'':59B ''cycles'':15B,84B,248B ''dedicat'':135B ''deeply'':198B ''deity'':126B ''desert'':123B ''despit'':222B ''destini'':189B ''destroy'':131B ''destruction'':11B ''devot'':146B ''devours'':40B ''divin'':256B ''dominion'':162B ''echo'':85B ''eight'':255B ''embodi'':24B ''endless'':14B ''entir'':41B ''eternal'':58B ''existenc'':17B ''far'':96B ''first'':21B,68B ''fix'':188B ''followers'':231B ''for'':94B ''form'':78B ''fusion'':26B ''god'':8B,160B,245B ''groups'':166B ''hav'':101B,232B ''heritag'':229B ''his'':230B ''how'':71B ''hunding'':173B ''imperial'':238B ''in'':36B,190B,200B,227B ''influenc'':181B ''influencing'':203B ''inspir'':60B ''interpret'':178B ''into'':150B '